		<content type="html" xml:base="http://love2d.org/forums/viewtopic.php?p=31234#p31234"><![CDATA[
I need your opinion guys. I want to add string interpolation, but I'd like some opinions on the style of how to do this. Firstly what syntax do you think is good. The two I have in mind is:<div class="codebox"><p>Code: </p><pre><code>"#{i * 42}. Say hello."</code></pre></div>(Ruby syntax), or<div class="codebox"><p>Code: </p><pre><code>"$i * 42$. Say hello."</code></pre></div>(as seen in the reference manual). Being a Rubyist, I prefer the first out of those two of course.<br><br>Next is how to parse it. It'll need to be done by a method. My options here are:<br><br>1. When the call syntax is used with no arguments, it parse the string for interpolation.<div class="codebox"><p>Code: </p><pre><code>("#{i * 42}. Say hello.")()</code></pre></div>2. A normal method, named run or something (suggestions on name?).<div class="codebox"><p>Code: </p><pre><code>("#{i * 42}. Say hello."):run() -- or("#{i * 42}. Say hello."):parse()</code></pre></div>I tend to prefer the first, because it fits nicely with the syntax normally used with <a href="https://www.lua.org/manual/5.1/manual.html#pdf-loadstring">loadstring</a>:<div class="codebox"><p>Code: </p><pre><code>loadstring("foo = 3")()</code></pre></div>So what do you think?<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://love2d.org/forums/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=1722">BlackBulletIV</a> — Mon May 09, 2011 10:51 am</p><hr />
